Note: HIR to Ruby Translator for Translation Translation System
Note: Converts High-level Intermediate Representation to Ruby code


@Reasoning:
Encapsulates the entire mutable state of an HIR-to-Ruby emission pass so
translate_hir_to_ruby and its helpers can append text, track nesting, and
decide method-vs-block syntax without a global. current_class and
current_method are explicit (rather than implied by a stack) because Ruby
generation rarely nests more than one of each and requires the names for
self-referential constructs like alias_method and super.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
output_buffer accumulates the emitted Ruby source via emit (string_concat).
indentation_level is incremented by indent and decremented by dedent;
emit_indent writes two spaces per level. current_class is set by
translate_class and cleared on End class; current_method is set by
translate_function and cleared on its End. requires_newline is a single-shot
flag set by emit_newline so translate_statement_list can avoid double
newlines after constructs that already terminated their own line.
@End Implementation
Type called "HIRToRubyTranslator":
    output_buffer as String
    indentation_level as Integer
    current_class as String
    current_method as String
    requires_newline as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Factory ensuring every HIRToRubyTranslator starts in a clean state so a
single backend invocation can never inherit leftover indentation or class
context from a prior call. Zero-initializing requires_newline avoids the
first statement emitting a leading blank line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs an HIRToRubyTranslator with output_buffer = "", indentation_level
= 0, current_class = "", current_method = "", and requires_newline = 0.
Returns the value directly; callers store it in a local and pass it by
reference to all translate_* / emit_* helpers.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_hir_to_ruby_translator" returns Integer:
    Note: Create new HIR to Ruby translator instance

    Let translator be a value of type HIRToRubyTranslator with
        output_buffer as "",
        indentation_level as 0,
        current_class as "",
        current_method as "",
        requires_newline as 0

    Return translator
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Single-arg wrapper matching the central dispatcher call shape in
Note: translation.runa: `Return proc hir_to_ruby from RubyEmitter with hir_root`.
Note: Constructs a fresh HIRToRubyTranslator and routes through
Note: translate_hir_to_ruby which holds the actual translation pipeline.
Note: Introduced in P2-F Round 2B alongside the demolition of the vestigial
Note: ruby_emitter.runa shim.
@Reasoning:
Provides the dispatcher-shaped single-argument entry point so the central
translation router in translation.runa can invoke the Ruby backend
uniformly with every other language backend (Lua, Python, etc.) without
backend-specific argument shapes. Failure to construct a translator
returns 0 to surface allocation issues to the dispatcher rather than
producing partial output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guards against a 0 hir_root by returning 0. Allocates a fresh translator
via create_hir_to_ruby_translator; if that allocation returns 0, propagates
the failure. Otherwise calls translate_hir_to_ruby with the new translator
and the HIR root, returning the resulting Ruby code string.
@End Implementation
Process called "hir_to_ruby" takes hir_root as Integer returns Integer:
    If hir_root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let translator be proc create_hir_to_ruby_translator
    If translator is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ruby_code be proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, hir_root
    Return ruby_code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Central HIR-node dispatcher: every Ruby-emitting helper is reached by a
single match on the "node_type" key set by the HIR builder. Keeping the
dispatcher in one place means new HIR node kinds need exactly one new arm
added here plus the dedicated translate_* helper, rather than scattered
type checks across the file. The Otherwise arm emits a "# Unknown HIR
node" comment so unsupported nodes degrade visibly rather than silently
producing wrong code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node_type via get_dict_value and matches on every supported HIR kind
(module, class, function, block, conditional, loop, assignment, call,
super_call, yield, return, break, next, identifier, string_literal,
interpolated_string, number_literal, symbol, array_literal, hash_literal,
range, binary_operation, unary_operation, include, extend, alias, attr_*).
Returns translator.output_buffer after all recursive emission completes so
the caller sees the accumulated Ruby source as the function result.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_hir_to_ruby" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns String:
    Note: Translate HIR to Ruby code with complete language feature support

    Let node_type be proc get_dict_value with hir, "node_type"

    Match node_type:
        When "module":
            proc translate_module with translator, hir
        When "class":
            proc translate_class with translator, hir
        When "function":
            proc translate_function with translator, hir
        When "block":
            proc translate_block with translator, hir
        When "conditional":
            proc translate_conditional with translator, hir
        When "loop":
            proc translate_loop with translator, hir
        When "assignment":
            proc translate_assignment with translator, hir
        When "call":
            proc translate_call with translator, hir
        When "super_call":
            proc translate_super_call with translator, hir
        When "yield":
            proc translate_yield with translator, hir
        When "return":
            proc translate_return with translator, hir
        When "break":
            proc translate_break with translator, hir
        When "next":
            proc translate_next with translator, hir
        When "identifier":
            proc translate_identifier with translator, hir
        When "string_literal":
            proc translate_string_literal with translator, hir
        When "interpolated_string":
            proc translate_interpolated_string with translator, hir
        When "number_literal":
            proc translate_number_literal with translator, hir
        When "symbol":
            proc translate_symbol with translator, hir
        When "array_literal":
            proc translate_array_literal with translator, hir
        When "hash_literal":
            proc translate_hash_literal with translator, hir
        When "range":
            proc translate_range with translator, hir
        When "binary_operation":
            proc translate_binary_operation with translator, hir
        When "unary_operation":
            proc translate_unary_operation with translator, hir
        When "include":
            proc translate_include with translator, hir
        When "extend":
            proc translate_extend with translator, hir
        When "alias":
            proc translate_alias with translator, hir
        When "attr_accessor":
            proc translate_attr_accessor with translator, hir
        When "attr_reader":
            proc translate_attr_reader with translator, hir
        When "attr_writer":
            proc translate_attr_writer with translator, hir
        Otherwise:
            proc emit with translator, "# Unknown HIR node: "
            proc emit with translator, node_type
    End Match

    Return translator.output_buffer
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR modules map cleanly to Ruby's `module ... end` construct (not class) so
namespacing without instantiation is preserved across the round-trip. The
body is emitted at one indent level deeper than the module header to
respect Ruby's idiomatic two-space indentation as enforced by emit_indent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the "name" field, emits "module <name>" followed by newline, calls
indent() to push one level, recursively emits the body via
translate_statement_list (skipped when body is 0), then dedent() and a
final "end" via emit_line. No tracking of nested modules is required
because indent/dedent are scope-symmetric.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_module" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR module to Ruby module

    Let module_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "name"

    proc emit with translator, "module "
    proc emit with translator, module_name
    proc emit_newline from translator

    proc indent from translator

    Note: Translate module body
    Let body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "body"
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_statement_list with translator, body
    End If

    proc dedent from translator
    proc emit_line with translator, "end"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby class emission must couple single inheritance (the `<` operator) with
mixin lists (include/extend) that appear after the class opener but before
any methods. Updating translator.current_class lets nested constructs
(method definitions, alias statements) reference the enclosing class by
name without re-reading the HIR node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets translator.current_class to the class name read from HIR, emits
"class <name>". If a superclass HIR node exists, emits " < " and
recursively translates it (rather than reading a name string, since the
superclass can be a constant expression like Foo::Bar). After the header
newline, indent(), then translate_mixins for include/extend lists, then
translate_statement_list for the body. Dedent(), emit_line "end", and
restore current_class to "" so subsequent top-level emission is correct.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_class" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR class to Ruby class with inheritance and mixins

    Let class_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "name"
    Set translator.current_class to class_name

    proc emit with translator, "class "
    proc emit with translator, class_name

    Note: Handle inheritance
    Let superclass be proc get_dict_value with hir, "superclass"
    If superclass is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with translator, " < "
        proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, superclass
    End If

    proc emit_newline from translator
    proc indent from translator

    Note: Handle mixins first
    proc translate_mixins with translator, hir

    Note: Translate class body
    Let body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "body"
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_statement_list with translator, body
    End If

    proc dedent from translator
    proc emit_line with translator, "end"

    Set translator.current_class to ""

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR "function" emits as Ruby `def ... end` whether at class scope (instance
method), module scope (module method), or top level (private method on
Object). Empty bodies become a `# Empty method` comment rather than no
body so the resulting Ruby remains syntactically valid and the round-trip
preserves the distinction between absent and empty.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets translator.current_method to the method name for downstream
super-call resolution. Emits "def <name>". If parameters is non-zero,
wraps them in "()" via translate_parameters. After header newline,
indent(), then translate_statement_list on the body (or emits an empty
method comment if body is 0). Dedent, emit_line "end", restore
current_method to "".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_function" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR function to Ruby method

    Let method_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "name"
    Set translator.current_method to method_name

    proc emit with translator, "def "
    proc emit with translator, method_name

    Note: Handle parameters
    Let parameters be proc get_dict_value with hir, "parameters"
    If parameters is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with translator, "("
        proc translate_parameters with translator, parameters
        proc emit with translator, ")"
    End If

    proc emit_newline from translator
    proc indent from translator

    Note: Translate method body
    Let body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "body"
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_statement_list with translator, body
    Otherwise:
        Note: Empty method body
        proc emit_line with translator, "# Empty method"
    End If

    proc dedent from translator
    proc emit_line with translator, "end"

    Set translator.current_method to ""

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby parameter lists carry four orthogonal annotations - splat (`*args`),
double-splat (`**kwargs`), block (`&blk`), and default-valued (`x = expr`)
- each requiring different sigil placement. Centralizing the per-parameter
dispatch here keeps callers (translate_function, translate_block) free of
sigil knowledge and ensures the leading comma is emitted only between
parameters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the parameter list by index. Emits ", " between parameters
(index > 0). For each parameter reads "type" and "name". Matches on type:
"splat" emits "*name", "double_splat" emits "**name", "block" emits
"&name", and the default arm emits just "name" plus, if a "default" HIR
node is attached, " = " followed by a recursive translate_hir_to_ruby on
that default expression.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_parameters" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, params as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR parameters to Ruby parameter syntax

    Let param_count be proc get_list_size from params
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than param_count:
        If index is greater than 0:
            proc emit with translator, ", "
        End If

        Let param be proc get_list_item with params, index
        Let param_type be proc get_dict_value with param, "type"
        Let param_name be proc get_dict_value with param, "name"

        Note: Handle different parameter types
        Match param_type:
            When "splat":
                proc emit with translator, "*"
                proc emit with translator, param_name
            When "double_splat":
                proc emit with translator, "**"
                proc emit with translator, param_name
            When "block":
                proc emit with translator, "&"
                proc emit with translator, param_name
            Otherwise:
                proc emit with translator, param_name

                Note: Handle default values
                Let default_value be proc get_dict_value with param, "default"
                If default_value is not equal to 0:
                    proc emit with translator, " = "
                    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, default_value
                End If
        End Match

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby has two block syntaxes - `{ ... }` (single-line, high precedence) and
`do ... end` (multi-line, low precedence) - and idiomatic Ruby uses the
braces form only for trivial bodies. is_simple_block heuristically picks
between them so the emitter matches conventional Ruby formatting rather
than always defaulting to one form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_simple_block to decide. Single-line: emits "{ ", optionally
"|params| " using translate_block_parameters, then statement list, then
" }". Multi-line: emits "do", optionally " |params|", newline, indent,
statement list, dedent, emit_line "end". Parameter pipes are emitted only
when the parameters HIR node is non-zero.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_block" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR block to Ruby block

    Let parameters be proc get_dict_value with hir, "parameters"
    Let body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "body"

    Note: Determine block style based on complexity
    Let is_single_line be proc is_simple_block from body

    If is_single_line is equal to 1:
        proc emit with translator, "{ "

        If parameters is not equal to 0:
            proc emit with translator, "|"
            proc translate_block_parameters with translator, parameters
            proc emit with translator, "| "
        End If

        proc translate_statement_list with translator, body
        proc emit with translator, " }"
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with translator, "do"

        If parameters is not equal to 0:
            proc emit with translator, " |"
            proc translate_block_parameters with translator, parameters
            proc emit with translator, "|"
        End If

        proc emit_newline from translator
        proc indent from translator

        proc translate_statement_list with translator, body

        proc dedent from translator
        proc emit_line with translator, "end"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby `if/elsif/else/end` requires the elsif clauses to be flattened into a
linear chain at emission - HIR can carry them either as a nested
conditional or as an explicit elsif_clauses list, and this emitter assumes
the latter shape produced by the Ruby frontend. Else is always last and
optional.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads condition, then_body, else_body, elsif_clauses from the HIR node.
Emits "if <cond>", newline, indent, then_body via
translate_statement_list, dedent. For each elsif in elsif_clauses (a
list), emits "elsif <cond>", newline, indent, body, dedent. If else_body
is set, emit_line "else", indent, body, dedent. Final emit_line "end".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_conditional" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR conditional to Ruby if statement

    Let condition be proc get_dict_value with hir, "condition"
    Let then_body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "then_body"
    Let else_body be proc get_dict_value with hir, "else_body"
    Let elsif_clauses be proc get_dict_value with hir, "elsif_clauses"

    proc emit with translator, "if "
    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, condition
    proc emit_newline from translator

    proc indent from translator
    If then_body is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_statement_list with translator, then_body
    End If
    proc dedent from translator

    Note: Handle elsif clauses
    If elsif_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let elsif_count be proc get_list_size from elsif_clauses
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than elsif_count:
            Let elsif_clause be proc get_list_item with elsif_clauses, index
            Let elsif_condition be proc get_dict_value with elsif_clause, "condition"
            Let elsif_body be proc get_dict_value with elsif_clause, "then_body"

            proc emit with translator, "elsif "
            proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, elsif_condition
            proc emit_newline from translator

            proc indent from translator
            If elsif_body is not equal to 0:
                proc translate_statement_list with translator, elsif_body
            End If
            proc dedent from translator

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Handle else clause
    If else_body is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_line with translator, "else"
        proc indent from translator
        proc translate_statement_list with translator, else_body
        proc dedent from translator
    End If

    proc emit_line with translator, "end"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby method calls have four optional pieces - receiver, method name,
arguments, and trailing block - and Ruby omits the parentheses around an
empty argument list. Emitting "()" with zero arguments would still be
valid Ruby but would change idiomatic round-tripped output, so we only
emit parens when arg_count > 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads receiver, method (name), arguments, block from HIR. If receiver is
non-zero, recursively translates it and emits ".". Always emits the
method name. If arguments is non-zero, computes arg_count via
get_list_size; only when it is > 0 emits "(", translate_arguments, ")".
Finally if block is non-zero emits " " followed by translate_block.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_call" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR call to Ruby method call

    Let receiver be proc get_dict_value with hir, "receiver"
    Let method_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "method"
    Let arguments be proc get_dict_value with hir, "arguments"
    Let block be proc get_dict_value with hir, "block"

    Note: Handle receiver
    If receiver is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, receiver
        proc emit with translator, "."
    End If

    proc emit with translator, method_name

    Note: Handle arguments
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_count be proc get_list_size from arguments
        If arg_count is greater than 0:
            proc emit with translator, "("
            proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
            proc emit with translator, ")"
        End If
    End If

    Note: Handle block
    If block is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with translator, " "
        proc translate_block with translator, block
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR assignment node carries its operator as a string so compound forms
(`+=`, `||=`, `&&=`, `-=`, etc.) round-trip without requiring a separate
node kind per operator. We emit the target, the spaced operator, then the
value - matching Ruby's whitespace conventions for both simple `=` and
compound forms.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads target, value, operator from HIR. Recursively emits target,
" <operator> ", then recursively emits value. No special-casing for
chained assignment (`a = b = c`) because the HIR builder produces nested
assignment nodes that recurse naturally through this code path.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_assignment" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR assignment to Ruby assignment

    Let target be proc get_dict_value with hir, "target"
    Let value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "value"
    Let operator be proc get_dict_value with hir, "operator"

    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, target
    proc emit with translator, " "
    proc emit with translator, operator
    proc emit with translator, " "
    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby array literals use square brackets with comma-separated elements.
The empty-array case (`[]`) is naturally handled by the same path because
the inner loop simply doesn't execute when the elements list is absent
or empty, so no dedicated empty-case branch is needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "[". Reads "elements" from HIR; if non-zero iterates by index,
emitting ", " between elements (index > 0) and recursively translating
each element. Closes with "]". The leading comma is gated by index > 0
rather than a trailing comma to avoid invalid Ruby like `[1, 2, ]`.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_array_literal" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR array to Ruby array literal

    proc emit with translator, "["

    Let elements be proc get_dict_value with hir, "elements"
    If elements is not equal to 0:
        Let element_count be proc get_list_size from elements
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than element_count:
            If index is greater than 0:
                proc emit with translator, ", "
            End If

            Let element be proc get_list_item with elements, index
            proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, element

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit with translator, "]"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby hash syntax has two key-style conventions: `:key => value` (legacy,
required for non-symbol keys) and the modern `key: value` (only valid
when the key is a symbol). Emitting the modern form for symbol keys
preserves idiomatic Ruby in the round-trip; falling back to `=>` for any
other key type keeps the emitter correct for string, integer, and
expression keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "{". For each pair, reads key and value; checks key.node_type. If
"symbol", emits the symbol's "value" field followed by ": " (modern
syntax). Otherwise recursively translates the key and emits " => "
(legacy syntax). Then recursively translates value. Pairs are separated
by ", " (gated by index > 0). Closes with "}".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_hash_literal" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR hash to Ruby hash literal

    proc emit with translator, "{"

    Let pairs be proc get_dict_value with hir, "pairs"
    If pairs is not equal to 0:
        Let pair_count be proc get_list_size from pairs
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than pair_count:
            If index is greater than 0:
                proc emit with translator, ", "
            End If

            Let pair be proc get_list_item with pairs, index
            Let key be proc get_dict_value with pair, "key"
            Let value be proc get_dict_value with pair, "value"

            Note: Use modern hash syntax for symbol keys when possible
            Let key_type be proc get_dict_value with key, "node_type"
            If key_type is equal to "symbol":
                Let symbol_value be proc get_dict_value with key, "value"
                proc emit with translator, symbol_value
                proc emit with translator, ": "
            Otherwise:
                proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, key
                proc emit with translator, " => "
            End If

            proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, value

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit with translator, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby symbols are immutable interned strings prefixed with `:` and the HIR
stores the symbol's textual content (without the colon) under the "value"
key. The emitter just prepends the sigil. No escaping is required because
symbol values valid in the HIR are already drawn from the Ruby identifier
alphabet plus operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits ":" then the symbol "value" via emit. No quoting is attempted -
even though Ruby supports `:"with spaces"`, the HIR shape coming from
ruby_parser never produces a quoted symbol so emitting unquoted is the
correct round-trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_symbol" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR symbol to Ruby symbol

    proc emit with translator, ":"
    Let value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "value"
    proc emit with translator, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Plain (non-interpolated) string literals always use double quotes for
emission so a single helper escapes special characters consistently. Using
double quotes for all literals (rather than mixing with single quotes) is
a deliberate normalization step - it loses the source's quote-style choice
but ensures escape_ruby_string is the only escaping path needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `"`, reads "value" from HIR, runs it through escape_ruby_string to
backslash-escape `"`, `\`, `\n`, `\t`, `\r`, then emits the closing `"`.
The escape pass is mandatory because user source may legitimately contain
unescaped quotes inside single-quoted source literals that have already
been decoded by the parser.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Inputs may originate from untrusted source code. escape_ruby_string is
the single point of containment so that no raw quote or backslash escapes
the emitted literal and corrupts surrounding Ruby code.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "translate_string_literal" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR string to Ruby string literal

    proc emit with translator, "\""
    Let value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "value"
    Let escaped_value be proc escape_ruby_string from value
    proc emit with translator, escaped_value
    proc emit with translator, "\""

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby interpolated strings (`"...#{expr}..."`) are stored in HIR as a
"parts" list interleaving literal text fragments with arbitrary
expression nodes. Only literal segments are passed through
escape_ruby_string; expression segments are wrapped in `#{...}` and
translated recursively, preserving the dynamic-evaluation semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits opening `"`. For each part: if its node_type is "string_literal",
escape its value and emit raw. Otherwise wrap with `#{` and `}` around a
recursive translate_hir_to_ruby call on the expression. Emits closing
`"`. The all-literal case (no expression parts) still passes through
because the parts list is just a sequence of string_literal nodes.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Literal segments carry the same untrusted-source risk as plain string
literals and are escaped via escape_ruby_string. Expression segments are
translated as HIR and therefore re-emit via the same dispatcher that
applied to all other code; they are not raw strings inserted into Ruby
source.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "translate_interpolated_string" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR interpolated string to Ruby interpolated string

    proc emit with translator, "\""

    Let parts be proc get_dict_value with hir, "parts"
    If parts is not equal to 0:
        Let part_count be proc get_list_size from parts
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than part_count:
            Let part be proc get_list_item with parts, index
            Let part_type be proc get_dict_value with part, "node_type"

            If part_type is equal to "string_literal":
                Let text_value be proc get_dict_value with part, "value"
                Let escaped_text be proc escape_ruby_string from text_value
                proc emit with translator, escaped_text
            Otherwise:
                proc emit with translator, "#{"
                proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, part
                proc emit with translator, "}"
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit with translator, "\""

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Numeric literals are stored as their already-stringified textual
representation in the HIR (which preserves base prefixes like `0x`, `0o`,
underscores like `1_000_000`, and scientific notation), so the emitter
simply writes the stored text without re-parsing. Re-parsing would lose
formatting like underscore separators on a round-trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "value" from HIR and emits it verbatim. No type tag is read because
Ruby does not require integer/float disambiguation at the literal level -
`1` and `1.0` are distinguished purely by the textual form.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_number_literal" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR number to Ruby number literal

    Let value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "value"
    proc emit with translator, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Operator precedence in Ruby requires explicit parentheses only when a
child operation has lower precedence than its parent (e.g., `(a + b) * c`
must keep parens, but `a * (b * c)` need not). needs_parentheses
encapsulates this lookup so emission is purely structural - no parens
are emitted otherwise to keep output readable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads left, operator, right from HIR. Calls needs_parentheses with the
HIR node and its operator string. If 1, emits "(". Recursively emits
left, emits " <operator> ", recursively emits right. If parens were
opened, closes with ")". Spacing around the operator is unconditional
because all multi-character Ruby operators (`**`, `<=>`, `<<`) tolerate
surrounding whitespace.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_binary_operation" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR binary operation to Ruby binary expression

    Let left be proc get_dict_value with hir, "left"
    Let operator be proc get_dict_value with hir, "operator"
    Let right be proc get_dict_value with hir, "right"

    Note: Handle operator precedence with parentheses when needed
    Let needs_parens be proc needs_parentheses with hir, operator

    If needs_parens is equal to 1:
        proc emit with translator, "("
    End If

    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, left
    proc emit with translator, " "
    proc emit with translator, operator
    proc emit with translator, " "
    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, right

    If needs_parens is equal to 1:
        proc emit with translator, ")"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby ranges distinguish inclusive (`..`) and exclusive (`...`) endpoints,
and the HIR carries the choice as the "operator" field rather than two
node kinds. Defaulting to `..` for any non-"..." string keeps the
emitter robust against frontends that omit the operator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads start, end, operator from HIR. Recursively emits the start
expression, emits "..." iff operator equals "..." otherwise "..", then
recursively emits the end expression. No whitespace is inserted around
the range operator because Ruby treats `1..10` and `1 .. 10` differently
in argument position (the latter can be parsed as a call argument plus
range).
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_range" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR range to Ruby range

    Let start_value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "start"
    Let end_value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "end"
    Let operator be proc get_dict_value with hir, "operator"

    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, start_value

    Note: Use appropriate range operator
    If operator is equal to "...":
        proc emit with translator, "..."
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with translator, ".."
    End If

    proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, end_value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier emission is intentionally a single emit of the stored name -
Ruby's sigil-based name classification (`@`, `@@`, `$`) is preserved
inside the HIR identifier's "name" field by the parser, so no
classification logic belongs here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "name" from HIR and emits it via emit. Local variable, instance
variable (`@x`), class variable (`@@x`), and global (`$x`) references all
flow through this same path because the sigils are kept as part of the
name string by the Ruby frontend.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_identifier" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR identifier to Ruby variable

    Let name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "name"
    proc emit with translator, name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby methods return the value of their last expression implicitly, so an
explicit `return` keyword is redundant in that position. The HIR carries
an "implicit" flag (as a string "true") set by the Ruby frontend for any
return that appears as the last statement of a method body; this emitter
elides the keyword in that case to preserve idiomatic Ruby on round-trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value and implicit from HIR. If implicit equals the string "true",
recursively emits only the value (no `return` keyword). Otherwise emits
"return"; if value is non-zero, emits " " followed by a recursive
translation of the value. A `return` with no value is emitted as bare
`return` and is valid Ruby (returns nil).
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_return" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR return to Ruby return statement

    Let value be proc get_dict_value with hir, "value"
    Let is_implicit be proc get_dict_value with hir, "implicit"

    Note: Handle implicit returns (Ruby's last expression semantics)
    If is_implicit is equal to "true":
        Note: Don't emit explicit return for implicit returns
        proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, value
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with translator, "return"
        If value is not equal to 0:
            proc emit with translator, " "
            proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, value
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's `yield` invokes the block argument passed to the enclosing method
and uniquely omits parentheses when bare: `yield`, `yield x`, `yield x, y`
are all valid without parens. We emit the bare form to remain idiomatic;
parens are only needed when arguments collide with method-call precedence,
which translate_arguments handles upstream when those arguments are
emitted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "yield". If arguments HIR is non-zero, emits " " then defers to
translate_arguments which writes a comma-separated list. No `()` wrappers
are added because yield's grammar accepts a bare argument list at
statement position.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_yield" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR yield to Ruby yield statement

    proc emit with translator, "yield"

    Let arguments be proc get_dict_value with hir, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with translator, " "
        proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby distinguishes `super` (forwards the caller's arguments verbatim) from
`super()` (passes no arguments) - these have different semantics. The HIR
carries arguments as a list whose presence (non-zero) signals the explicit
form. Bare `super` is therefore emitted only when arguments is 0;
emit `super()` for explicit empty argument lists too via this same path
(arguments-list is present but empty).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "super". If arguments is non-zero, emits "(", calls
translate_arguments to fill the parenthesized list, then ")". An absent
arguments field (0) leaves the bare `super` form.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_super_call" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR super call to Ruby super

    proc emit with translator, "super"

    Let arguments be proc get_dict_value with hir, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with translator, "("
        proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
        proc emit with translator, ")"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby `include` mixes in instance methods from a module into the receiver
class. translate_mixins emits include directives inside the class body
before any methods so the resulting Ruby matches conventional ordering;
this helper only writes the include line itself.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "include ", reads the "module" name field from the HIR include
node, emits it raw (module references in HIR are pre-stringified, e.g.
"Comparable" or "ActiveSupport::Concern").
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_include" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR include to Ruby include statement

    proc emit with translator, "include "
    Let module_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "module"
    proc emit with translator, module_name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby `extend` mixes module methods as class (singleton) methods of the
receiver, the dual of `include`. Same structural shape as
translate_include but a different keyword - kept as a separate process
so the dispatcher can pick the right one without inspecting node fields.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "extend ", reads "module" from HIR, emits the module reference
verbatim.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_extend" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR extend to Ruby extend statement

    proc emit with translator, "extend "
    Let module_name be proc get_dict_value with hir, "module"
    proc emit with translator, module_name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's `attr_accessor` is a class-level macro generating both reader and
writer methods for the named symbols. The HIR carries a list of attribute
names that need to be emitted as `:name1, :name2, ...`. Delegated to
translate_attribute_list so the same emission shape can be reused by the
reader/writer-only variants if needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "attr_accessor ", reads "attributes" list from HIR, defers to
translate_attribute_list (defined in the shared helpers section) to emit
the comma-separated symbol list.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_attr_accessor" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR attr_accessor to Ruby attr_accessor

    proc emit with translator, "attr_accessor "
    Let attributes be proc get_dict_value with hir, "attributes"
    proc translate_attribute_list with translator, attributes

    Return 1
End Process

Note: Helper processes for HIR to Ruby translation

@Reasoning:
A statement list is emitted as a sequence of indented lines. Some emitted
constructs (if/end, def/end, do/end) already terminate with their own
newline; if this helper unconditionally appended one, the output would
contain blank lines between every multi-line construct. The
requires_newline flag is the coordination mechanism: emit_newline sets it,
and this loop consults it before adding another newline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each statement in the list: emits proper indentation via emit_indent,
recursively translates the statement, then conditionally adds a newline
only when requires_newline is still 0 (meaning the statement did not
self-terminate). Resets requires_newline to 0 after each iteration so the
next statement starts in a known state.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_statement_list" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, statements as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate list of HIR statements to Ruby statements

    Let stmt_count be proc get_list_size from statements
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than stmt_count:
        Let statement be proc get_list_item with statements, index

        proc emit_indent from translator
        proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, statement

        Note: Add newline unless it's already handled
        If translator.requires_newline is equal to 0:
            proc emit_newline from translator
        End If

        Set translator.requires_newline to 0
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Argument lists at call sites are just comma-separated expressions. The
caller (translate_call, translate_yield, translate_super_call) is
responsible for emitting any surrounding `(...)`; this helper writes only
the comma-separated payload so it can be reused in paren-less contexts
like yield.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the args list by index. For each argument, emits ", " between
items (index > 0) and recursively translates the argument expression via
translate_hir_to_ruby. The leading comma is gated on index to prevent a
leading separator before the first argument.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_arguments" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, args as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate HIR arguments to Ruby argument list

    Let arg_count be proc get_list_size from args
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than arg_count:
        If index is greater than 0:
            proc emit with translator, ", "
        End If

        Let argument be proc get_list_item with args, index
        proc translate_hir_to_ruby with translator, argument

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby idiom places `include` and `extend` directives at the top of a class
body, before constants and methods. translate_class invokes this helper
immediately after entering the class body (post-indent) so the directives
appear in the conventional position with one entry per line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the "includes" list (if present) and, for each include node,
emits indent, defers to translate_include, then newline. Then does the
same for the "extends" list using translate_extend. The shared index
local is intentionally reused (Set index to 0) before the second loop to
restart counting cleanly.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_mixins" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate class mixins (includes and extends)

    Let includes be proc get_dict_value with hir, "includes"
    If includes is not equal to 0:
        Let include_count be proc get_list_size from includes
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than include_count:
            Let include_stmt be proc get_list_item with includes, index
            proc emit_indent from translator
            proc translate_include with translator, include_stmt
            proc emit_newline from translator
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let extends be proc get_dict_value with hir, "extends"
    If extends is not equal to 0:
        Let extend_count be proc get_list_size from extends
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than extend_count:
            Let extend_stmt be proc get_list_item with extends, index
            proc emit_indent from translator
            proc translate_extend with translator, extend_stmt
            proc emit_newline from translator
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single chokepoint for all text appended to the Ruby output. Centralizing
buffer mutation here lets every other helper stay free of string_concat
details and would also be the natural place to add buffer-resize
optimization later without touching emission sites.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Concatenates text onto translator.output_buffer via string_concat and
stores the new buffer back on the translator. Returns 1 unconditionally
since the only failure mode (out-of-memory) is handled at the allocator
level.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, text as String returns Integer:
    Note: Emit text to output buffer
    Set translator.output_buffer to proc string_concat with translator.output_buffer, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience for the very common "indent + text + newline" pattern used by
block terminators (`end`), section markers, and any standalone statement.
Removing the three-call boilerplate from every caller makes the emission
sites read more linearly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequences emit_indent, emit with the provided text, and emit_newline.
Returns 1. Note that emit_newline sets requires_newline so
translate_statement_list will skip the auto-newline after this call.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_line" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator, text as String returns Integer:
    Note: Emit line with proper indentation
    proc emit_indent from translator
    proc emit with translator, text
    proc emit_newline from translator
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wraps the literal newline emission and atomically toggles the
requires_newline flag so translate_statement_list knows the last write
already ended a line. Without this flag, a construct like `end\n` followed
by the loop's auto-newline would produce a blank line after every block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "\n" via emit and sets translator.requires_newline to 1. The flag
is cleared by translate_statement_list once it has decided whether to
suppress its own newline.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_newline" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator returns Integer:
    Note: Emit newline character
    proc emit with translator, "\n"
    Set translator.requires_newline to 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's idiomatic indent is two spaces per nesting level. Emitting the
spaces one-by-one (rather than building an indent string and concatenating
it) is acceptable here because indentation_level is bounded by realistic
source nesting (typically <10), so the loop is short and avoids managing
a separate indent buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes total_spaces = indentation_level * 2, then loops space_count
from 0 to total_spaces - 1 emitting a single space each iteration. Note
that translator.indentation_level is the field actually consulted; the
suite field is called indentation_level (not indent_level) - the type
declaration matches.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indent" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator returns Integer:
    Note: Emit proper indentation

    Let spaces_per_level be 2
    Let total_spaces be translator.indentation_level multiplied by spaces_per_level
    Let space_count be 0

    While space_count is less than total_spaces:
        proc emit with translator, " "
        Set space_count to space_count plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Increments indentation level for the duration of a nested block. Paired
with dedent so every translate_* helper that opens a body must close it,
guaranteeing balanced indentation on output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Adds 1 to translator.indentation_level. Has no effect on already-emitted
output; only future emit_indent calls observe the new level.
@End Implementation
Process called "indent" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator returns Integer:
    Note: Increase indentation level
    Set translator.indentation_level to translator.indentation_level plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decrements indentation level. Guards against going below zero so a buggy
caller emitting an extra dedent cannot underflow the level to a negative
value (which would compute a very large total_spaces under integer
arithmetic and emit a massive indent line).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Subtracts 1 from translator.indentation_level only when the current value
is greater than 0. Otherwise leaves it at 0 silently.
@End Implementation
Process called "dedent" takes translator as HIRToRubyTranslator returns Integer:
    Note: Decrease indentation level
    If translator.indentation_level is greater than 0:
        Set translator.indentation_level to translator.indentation_level minus 1
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby double-quoted strings interpret backslash sequences, so the literal
forms of `"`, `\`, newline, tab, and carriage return must each be
re-escaped before emission. Single-character matching is used rather than
regex because the surface alphabet is small and a switch is both faster
and easier to audit for completeness.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a result string by iterating text character-by-character. Match
arms:
- `"` => `\"`
- `\` => `\\`
- newline (LF) => `\n`
- tab => `\t`
- carriage return => `\r`
- any other char => emitted as-is.
Uses string_concat into result on each step. Returns the assembled
escaped string.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
This is the security boundary for emitted string literals. Any
unrecognized control character is passed through unchanged - that is safe
inside a double-quoted Ruby string because Ruby does not have additional
metacharacters beyond the five handled here. Embedded `#{...}` would still
be interpolated by Ruby; callers must use translate_interpolated_string
when interpolation is intended, not pass an already-interpolated string
through this helper.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "escape_ruby_string" takes text as String returns String:
    Note: Escape special characters in Ruby string

    Let result be ""
    Let length be length of text
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than length:
        Let char be proc char_at with text, index

        Match char:
            When "\"":
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, "\\\""
            When "\\":
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, "\\\\"
            When "\n":
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, "\\n"
            When "\t":
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, "\\t"
            When "\r":
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, "\\r"
            Otherwise:
                Set result to proc string_concat with result, char
        End Match

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heuristic gating between `{...}` and `do...end` block syntax. A body is
"simple" if it has exactly one statement and that statement is one of the
trivially-shaped kinds that look natural on a single line. Any other shape
(including control structures, multi-statement bodies, or assignments) is
classified as non-simple and translate_block uses `do...end`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 immediately if body is 0 (empty block) since an empty brace
form is fine. Otherwise rejects bodies with !=1 statement. Reads the
node_type of the lone statement and matches: "call", "identifier",
"string_literal", "number_literal", "binary_operation" map to single-line
eligible (Return 1); all other types return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_simple_block" takes body as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Determine if block body is simple enough for single-line syntax

    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let stmt_count be proc get_list_size from body
    If stmt_count is not equal to 1:
        Return 0  Note: Multiple statements require multi-line
    End If

    Let statement be proc get_list_item with body, 0
    Let stmt_type be proc get_dict_value with statement, "node_type"

    Note: Simple statements that can be single-line
    Match stmt_type:
        When "call":
            Return 1
        When "identifier":
            Return 1
        When "string_literal":
            Return 1
        When "number_literal":
            Return 1
        When "binary_operation":
            Return 1
        Otherwise:
            Return 0
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inferring whether a child binary operation needs parentheses in its
parent context requires knowing both operators' precedence. By comparing
the child operator's precedence against the parent's, we can drop
redundant parens that would otherwise clutter idiomatic Ruby output.
This is conservative: when uncertain (no parent context, unknown parent
operator), no parens are emitted - Ruby's default precedence handles
those cases correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null hir. Reads the parent node type via hir_get_node_type.
HIR_BINARY_OP is constant 25; if the parent is not a binary op, no parens
needed. Reads parent_op via hir_get_operator; if 0 (missing), no parens.
Compares get_ruby_operator_precedence(operator) against
get_ruby_operator_precedence(parent_op): if current < parent, the current
operation binds looser than its context and requires parens to preserve
associativity; otherwise no parens.
@End Implementation
Process called "needs_parentheses" takes hir as Integer, operator as String returns Integer:
    Note: Determine if binary operation needs parentheses based on Ruby operator precedence
    Note: Ruby precedence (high to low): **, unary +/-, *, /, %, +, -, <<, >>, &, |, ^, <=>, ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=, &&, ||, .., ..., ?:, =, and, or, not

    Note: Get parent expression context to check precedence
    Note: If no parent context or HIR is null, no parentheses needed
    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if parent is also a binary operation. The constant value 25
    Note: comes from HIR.HIR_BINARY_OP; we inline it here because there is no
    Note: HIR module Import in this file (which would cause a codegen "Unknown
    Note: variable 'HIR'" error). Keeping the value in sync with the canonical
    Note: definition in compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/
    Note: scala/scala_to_hir.runa is required.
    Let parent_type be proc hir_get_node_type from HIR with hir
    If parent_type is not equal to 25:
        Return 0  Note: Parent is not binary op, no parentheses needed
    End If

    Note: Get parent operator
    Let parent_op be proc hir_get_operator from HIR with hir
    If parent_op is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get precedence levels
    Let current_prec be proc get_ruby_operator_precedence from operator
    Let parent_prec be proc get_ruby_operator_precedence from parent_op

    Note: If current has lower precedence than parent, needs parentheses
    If current_prec is less than parent_prec:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Numeric precedence table for Ruby binary operators, returning higher
values for tighter binding. Encoded as a sequence of string-equality
checks rather than a hash lookup so the table is self-documenting,
trivially auditable against the Ruby language spec, and free of
dictionary overhead in this hot path (called twice per binary
operation by needs_parentheses).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns:
- 14: `**` (exponentiation, highest precedence excluding unary)
- 12: `*`, `/`, `%`
- 11: `+`, `-`
- 10: `<<`, `>>` (shifts)
-  9: `&` (bitwise AND)
-  8: `^` (bitwise XOR)
-  7: `|` (bitwise OR)
-  6: `<=>`, `..`, `...` (combined comparison / ranges)
-  5: `==`, `!=`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=` (and unknown default)
-  4: `&&`
-  3: `||`
-  2: `and` (keyword form, low precedence)
-  1: `or` (keyword form, lowest precedence)
Default Return 5 covers any operator not explicitly listed so unknown
inputs sort with the comparison group instead of an extreme value, which
keeps needs_parentheses safe against new operator strings.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_ruby_operator_precedence" takes operator as String returns Integer:
    Note: Return precedence level for Ruby operators (higher number = higher precedence)

    Note: Exponentiation (highest precedence)
    If operator is equal to "**":
        Return 14
    End If

    Note: Multiplication, division, modulo
    If operator is equal to "*":
        Return 12
    End If
    If operator is equal to "/":
        Return 12
    End If
    If operator is equal to "%":
        Return 12
    End If

    Note: Addition, subtraction
    If operator is equal to "+":
        Return 11
    End If
    If operator is equal to "-":
        Return 11
    End If

    Note: Bitwise shift
    If operator is equal to "<<":
        Return 10
    End If
    If operator is equal to ">>":
        Return 10
    End If

    Note: Bitwise AND
    If operator is equal to "&":
        Return 9
    End If

    Note: Bitwise XOR and OR
    If operator is equal to "^":
        Return 8
    End If
    If operator is equal to "|":
        Return 7
    End If

    Note: Comparison operators
    If operator is equal to "<=>":
        Return 6
    End If
    If operator is equal to "==":
        Return 5
    End If
    If operator is equal to "!=":
        Return 5
    End If
    If operator is equal to "<":
        Return 5
    End If
    If operator is equal to ">":
        Return 5
    End If
    If operator is equal to "<=":
        Return 5
    End If
    If operator is equal to ">=":
        Return 5
    End If

    Note: Logical AND
    If operator is equal to "&&":
        Return 4
    End If
    If operator is equal to "and":
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Logical OR
    If operator is equal to "||":
        Return 3
    End If
    If operator is equal to "or":
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Range operators
    If operator is equal to "..":
        Return 6
    End If
    If operator is equal to "...":
        Return 6
    End If

    Note: Default (unknown operator)
    Return 5
End Process